## üìÑ Summary

This repository documents a long-term, targeted intrusion against my systems across multiple devices and networks.

Attackers have installed **custom-modified Realtek wireless drivers** disguised as OEM (HP, Lenovo, ASUS, etc.), granting them deep **kernel and UEFI access**. Evidence also includes **PowerShell enumeration tools**, **C2 activity via cloud sync (OneDrive)**, **AWS Linux servers pinging Canary tokens**, and clear **registry-level wireless manipulation**.

> üìç This is not commodity malware. It‚Äôs a stealthy **NIC firmware mimic toolkit** capable of:
> - OEM vendor spoofing (e.g., HP8852Be-VT, ASUS8852Be-VT)
> - Driver mutation and version tailoring
> - Roaming/aggression control for wireless C2
> - BIOS/UEFI bypass logic (confirmed)
> - Telemetry, event log, and power state spoofing

---

## üß† Threat Anatomy

### ü™õ 1. OEM-Spoofed Driver Implant

| File Name                   | Notes                                   |
|----------------------------|-----------------------------------------|
| `vtwlane613.sys`           | Modified Realtek driver implant         |
| `vtldata613.txt`           | Driver parameters / behavior scripts    |
| `RoamingSensitivity.reg`   | Alters AP scan behavior                 |
| `RealWow.reg`, `PMEFollow.reg` | Wake-on-Wireless & stealth tuning  |

Confirmed `.NT`, `.NT.Services`, `.NT.HW` structure enables:
- Hardware spoofing per vendor
- Dynamic behavior for Dell, HP, ASUS
- Power management hijacking

